    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA97-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu paruvaṅ kaṇṭu āṟṟāḷāya talaivi tōḻikku uraittatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE, who was unable to bear it when seeing the season, said to [her] confidante.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA97">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            aḻuntupaṭu viḻuppuṇ vaḻumpuvāy pularā</l>
<l>            vevva neñcat teḵkeṟin tāṅkup</l>
<l>            pirivila pulampi nuvaluṅ kuyiliṉun</l>
<l>            tēṟunīr keḻīiya yāṟunaṉi koṭitē</l>
<l>            yataṉiṉuṅ koṭiyā ṭāṉē mataṉiṉ </l>
<l>            ṟuyttalai yitaḻa paiṅkuruk kattiyoṭu</l>
<l>            pittikai viravumalar koḷḷī rōveṉa</l>
<l>            vaṇṭucūḻ vaṭṭiya ṭiritarun</l>
<l>            taṇṭalai yuḻavar taṉimaṭa makaḷē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Much more cruel,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as a lance thrust into a troubled heart,</l>
<l rend="indent">the wet mouth of the long-standing, terrible(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">viḻu puṇ</term>: does <term xml:lang="ta">viḻu</term> "excellent" here simply refer to the extent of the wound or is the association that of an honourable wound in battle? Or do we have to think of <term xml:lang="ta">viḻumam</term> "distress" here?</note> wound not drying,</l>
<l>than the Koels that lament [and] talk, they not separated,</l>
<l rend="indent3">[is] the river filled with clear water.</l>
<l>Crueller than that [is] she herself, excessively(?)<note place="foot">Is there another way to understand <term xml:lang="ta">mataṉiṉ</term>?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">the sole innocent daughter of the ploughmen from the cool area,</l>
<l rend="indent2">who turns about the basket she holds, surrounded by bees,</l>
<l rend="indent4">saying</l>
<l rend="indent">“won't you take the mixed blossoms of the large-flowered jasmine</l>
<l rend="indent3">with the fresh Kurukkatti in cotton-headed clusters?”<note place="foot">For the topos of the woman passing the houses in order to sell flowers see NA 118.</note></l>
        </lg>
